WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.810 --> 00:00:06.050
CLIFF: So gathering in a room
full of people, many of whom

00:00:06.050 --> 00:00:07.880
are strangers,
it's something that

00:00:07.880 --> 00:00:10.280
feels uncomfortable
to a lot of us.

00:00:10.280 --> 00:00:14.460
Now Susan RoAne is here to
help fix that challenge.

00:00:14.460 --> 00:00:17.790
She's here to speak about
her landmark book-- currently

00:00:17.790 --> 00:00:20.320
celebrating its 25th
year of publication--

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:21.700
"How to Work a Room."

00:00:21.700 --> 00:00:26.180
It's sold over 1.2 million
copies in over 13 countries.

00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:28.540
And even though much of
our daily communication

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:30.900
involves technology, whether
it's in the workplace

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:33.300
or at a wedding or
at a fundraiser,

00:00:33.300 --> 00:00:36.380
we still need this bit of
face to face interaction.

00:00:36.380 --> 00:00:38.540
And that's what
Susan brings along.

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:42.200
Now, the book has gotten a wide
variety of press and acclaim,

00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:47.850
so she's shared information
about the book in various news

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:48.570
outlets.

00:00:48.570 --> 00:00:50.320
It's gotten some really
great endorsements

00:00:50.320 --> 00:00:53.540
from people such as Guy
Kawasaki and Daniel Pink.

00:00:53.540 --> 00:00:55.760
And Susan is a
professional speaker.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:00:59.160
And her clients range throughout
the industry, anywhere

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:01.540
from Coca Cola and
United Healthcare

00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:03.590
to the United States
Air Force, some

00:01:03.590 --> 00:01:05.620
of the folks down
at Apple or Oracle,

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.990
or on her current favorite,
which is Hershey's Chocolate.

00:01:08.990 --> 00:01:11.250
Now, on a personal
note, Susan did graduate

00:01:11.250 --> 00:01:14.550
from the University of Illinois,
as I did and many of us

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:15.540
here in the audience.

00:01:15.540 --> 00:01:19.120
So it's always great to bring
another bit of the Illini love

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:20.970
home here to Mountain View.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:22.990
And so without further
ado, please join me

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:26.040
in welcoming back to Authors
at Google, the keynote speaker,

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:29.344
bestselling author, and the
mingling maven, Susan RoAne.

00:01:29.344 --> 00:01:29.844
Thank you.

00:01:29.844 --> 00:01:33.874
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:33.874 --> 00:01:35.290
SUSAN ROANE: Well,
you heard Cliff

00:01:35.290 --> 00:01:37.331
say that I've been written
up in a lot of places.

00:01:37.331 --> 00:01:41.940
And this book is celebrating
its silver anniversary.

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:44.010
Someone asked me, why
would you write it again?

00:01:44.010 --> 00:01:45.920
This is the fourth iteration.

00:01:45.920 --> 00:01:49.550
And I said the last issue
that came out was 2007.

00:01:49.550 --> 00:01:52.010
I wrote it in 2006.

00:01:52.010 --> 00:01:55.570
And it's not that
people have changed.

00:01:55.570 --> 00:01:58.017
In fact, people still
want to be comfortable.

00:01:58.017 --> 00:01:59.350
They want to have conversations.

00:01:59.350 --> 00:02:00.400
We want to have fun.

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:01.770
We want to feel appreciated.

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:04.230
We want to feel listened to.

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:08.100
We want to feel that
we're important.

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:10.380
But what's changed
is technology.

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:13.170
When I first wrote "How to
Work a Room." the research

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:16.310
at Stanford's research clinic
by Doctor Phillip Zimbardo,

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:22.000
he found that 80% of American
adults self-identify as shy.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:23.230
That's a huge portion.

00:02:23.230 --> 00:02:25.600
By the time the third
iteration came out

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:29.620
in 2000, that jumped to 93%.

00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:32.540
They asked Doctor Zimbardo, what
do you attribute that big jump?

00:02:32.540 --> 00:02:33.210
That's huge.

00:02:33.210 --> 00:02:37.630
13% more people are
self-identifying as shy.

00:02:37.630 --> 00:02:42.250
And he said one
word-- "Technology."

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:45.940
Can you imagine now, 14 years
later, how we're communicating?

00:02:45.940 --> 00:02:48.316
How much technology
has changed us?

00:02:48.316 --> 00:02:49.440
But really, we're the same.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:51.990
It's just some of our
behaviors have changed.

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.250
I also rewrote it because
some of the things

00:02:54.250 --> 00:02:56.120
no longer applied.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:59.910
There are some terms
that would make no sense.

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:01.660
And there were things
I needed to add in.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:05.040
So there's a brand new chapter
called "New Rooms to Work."

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.190
And even though I had written
about LinkedIn and Facebook,

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:11.010
we now have this new
room called Twitter.

00:03:11.010 --> 00:03:15.392
And then there's Instagram,
and then there's Google+.

00:03:15.392 --> 00:03:17.560
So I had to include
that in the book.

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.180
And by the way, if anyone
wants to give me an additional

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:25.530
tutorial on Google+,
see me after the class.

00:03:25.530 --> 00:03:26.630
But I had to do that.

00:03:26.630 --> 00:03:29.400
Also, I'm originally
from Chicago,

00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:30.850
which is why I went to Illinois.

00:03:30.850 --> 00:03:34.430
And I had to delete things
of people who were dead

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:38.850
and-- if you'll forgive me--
people who were dead to me.

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:42.160
I took them out of the book.

00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:45.060
And I added in a chapter
called-- because I,

00:03:45.060 --> 00:03:48.380
again it's with the puns--
a whole chapter called

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:53.180
"Roominations," but I
spelled it R-O-O-M--

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:56.990
little tidbits to get you
through any event in any room.

00:03:56.990 --> 00:03:58.850
But writing a book
is interesting.

00:03:58.850 --> 00:04:00.900
By the way, writing
a book doesn't

00:04:00.900 --> 00:04:03.100
mean you dress up like this.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:05.500
It's, for me, on a
dining room table

00:04:05.500 --> 00:04:11.610
open twice the size with
the congratulatory chocolate

00:04:11.610 --> 00:04:12.880
at my left hand.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:14.450
That's how that worked.

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:16.430
And I've been asked
how I write my books.

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:18.120
What program do you use?

00:04:18.120 --> 00:04:23.560
Here's the program--
hand, number two pencil

00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:26.130
with good erasers,
and I didn't even

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:29.370
write on the back on
yellow legal paper,

00:04:29.370 --> 00:04:33.270
because that would be a
waste to this former teacher.

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:38.880
I write my books on
the back of used paper.

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:40.540
They call it recycling.

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:43.530
And someone once said,
well, that's cheap of you.

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:47.660
But I really thought it
was very forward thinking.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:49.890
It doesn't matter
how we write a book,

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:53.500
it matters that we write
a book, and that we just

00:04:53.500 --> 00:04:55.140
pick up whatever tool we use.

00:04:57.670 --> 00:05:00.800
"How to Work a Room" first
came out 25 years ago.

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:03.600
I'm a former school teacher
in San Francisco and Chicago.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:07.270
I was so excited,
because the "Wall Street

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:10.330
Journal" reviewed my book.

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:12.830
I was excited until
I read what it said.

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:14.350
So let me quote.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:16.160
I found out later
this review was

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:19.980
written by actually one of
my heroes, David Brooks, who

00:05:19.980 --> 00:05:21.760
now writes for the
New York Times.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:23.960
He thought he was
being satirical.

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:25.010
I didn't know that.

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:26.250
It broke my heart.

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:27.530
Here's what he wrote.

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:33.770
"At last, the perfect how-to
book for shallow people."

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:34.792
I was really upset.

00:05:34.792 --> 00:05:37.250
And then a gentleman who worked
for the Chamber of Commerce

00:05:37.250 --> 00:05:39.320
in San Francisco said
to me, you know nothing

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:40.961
about marketing, Susan.

00:05:40.961 --> 00:05:41.460
I don't?

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:43.647
He said, shallow
people, don't you

00:05:43.647 --> 00:05:49.410
know that's a market of 40 to 50
million potential book buyers?

00:05:49.410 --> 00:05:51.230
And by the way,
because all of you

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:55.420
are going to get your
Google special price book,

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:59.100
I know that the people who
bought "How to Work a Room"

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:00.390
aren't shallow.

00:06:00.390 --> 00:06:03.880
Based on the work of Doctor
Bernardo Carducci and Doctor

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:06.210
Zimbardo, who
specialize in shyness,

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:10.445
people bought the book
because we are shy.

00:06:10.445 --> 00:06:12.820
And it doesn't mean we're shy
at work when we know people

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:13.778
and see them every day.

00:06:13.778 --> 00:06:16.180
We might be shy if we're
invited to a party.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:19.410
I went to a wedding two
weeks ago in San Francisco,

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:23.140
and I only knew the
bride and the groom.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:24.070
The were busy.

00:06:24.070 --> 00:06:27.070
They didn't have
time to talk to me.

00:06:27.070 --> 00:06:30.890
I had to make sure that
I introduced myself

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:34.660
to people, talked
to them, et cetera.

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:36.800
Because that's on me.

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:38.700
Though there was,
at one point, I

00:06:38.700 --> 00:06:40.560
thought to myself,
oh my goodness.

00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:43.270
What did I write on page 230?

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:45.040
It might be helpful.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:46.610
But working a room is work.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.090
And you heard that I am
a professional speaker.

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:50.920
I speak about this all the time.

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:53.470
I actually just
came from Hollywood

00:06:53.470 --> 00:06:57.010
where I spoke about how to
work a room for a leadership

00:06:57.010 --> 00:07:00.510
conference for a global company.

00:07:00.510 --> 00:07:03.420
But right before my
speech, I went over

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:06.390
to Universal City Walk,
because I actually

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:11.270
wanted to the see King Kong
hanging from the rafters.

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:13.120
And I took a picture of it.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:16.120
But as I got off the
little shuttle bus,

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:19.570
I saw a man and a
woman walking this way.

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:22.410
I was walking into
the City Walk.

00:07:22.410 --> 00:07:25.410
Strangers next to me, and
the guy looked familiar.

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:27.580
And I did a double take.

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:30.910
And then I said to these
guys that I didn't know,

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:34.510
that looks like
Sugar Ray Leonard.

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:36.160
The guy said to
me, well, that is.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:40.550
And in a split second, I
had to make a decision.

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.770
Was I going to
continue, or was I

00:07:42.770 --> 00:07:45.500
going to go over and
meet Sugar Ray Leonard?

00:07:45.500 --> 00:07:49.051
And I thought, this is a once
in a lifetime opportunity.

00:07:49.051 --> 00:07:51.300
Have any of you had that
happen, where you see someone

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:52.925
and you know if you
don't say anything,

00:07:52.925 --> 00:07:54.780
you'll never have
another opportunity?

00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:56.250
I decided to take it.

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:57.295
Because guess what?

00:07:57.295 --> 00:07:59.850
How do I not if I
wrote this book?

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:01.370
Who should listen to me?

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:03.340
So I went over and
I stood and waited

00:08:03.340 --> 00:08:07.750
while a gentleman who was a
big fight fan talked to him.

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:11.200
And then I stood in the
corner, and here's what he did.

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:16.340
The celebrity, this man
of great acclaim, saw me,

00:08:16.340 --> 00:08:20.300
and he walked over to me,
big smile on his face.

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:22.380
I knew he was the
champ, because guess

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:26.107
what it said on his
t-shirt-- "champ."

00:08:26.107 --> 00:08:28.315
I'm thinking I'm going to
get one that says "author,"

00:08:28.315 --> 00:08:30.570
and on the back say
"professional speaker."

00:08:30.570 --> 00:08:32.309
I thought it was
good advertising.

00:08:32.309 --> 00:08:35.390
Smile on his face,
and I got so giddy.

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:37.840
I said to him, I'm so excited.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:39.860
Could you please
make my heart flutter

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:42.350
and let me take
a picture of you?

00:08:42.350 --> 00:08:47.720
And Sugar Ray Leonard said no,
with a big smile, and said,

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:50.110
we have to take a
picture together.

00:08:52.640 --> 00:08:55.080
Be still my heart.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:09:01.930
With a smile on his face,
so friendly, so welcoming.

00:09:01.930 --> 00:09:05.120
You know, I think when you're
a big enough celebrity,

00:09:05.120 --> 00:09:06.630
you know how to behave.

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:09.270
And I wish he could give
lessons to the rest of them that

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:12.140
end up on TMZ.

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:15.610
By the way, I took
that tour the next day.

00:09:15.610 --> 00:09:17.280
But Sugar Ray Leonard did this.

00:09:17.280 --> 00:09:20.750
And as I was backing away
saying oh thank you so much,

00:09:20.750 --> 00:09:22.610
I'm so excited, I
did say to him--

00:09:22.610 --> 00:09:26.910
and got permission-- I said I'm
here to speak to a conference.

00:09:26.910 --> 00:09:30.450
And I said, I wrote "How to
Work a Room"-- shameless plug,

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:31.820
got that in to the champ.

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:33.980
And I said, would
it be OK with you

00:09:33.980 --> 00:09:36.540
if I tell the story how we met?

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:38.180
And he said, absolutely.

00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:40.240
And I was beginning to
walk away because I didn't

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:42.490
want to hog his time--
which, by the way,

00:09:42.490 --> 00:09:44.940
when you meet someone
who is of that celebrity,

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:48.040
whether it's Larry
or Sergei or whoever,

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:49.500
you don't want to
hog their time.

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:52.850
But you want to make
sure you talk to them.

00:09:52.850 --> 00:09:54.470
He said, wait a minute.

00:09:54.470 --> 00:09:58.220
Let's see if the
pictures turned out.

00:09:58.220 --> 00:09:59.590
How nice.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:00.710
How thoughtful.

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:02.310
How kind.

00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:02.980
And they did.

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:04.860
Of course, went
right up on Facebook.

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:05.641
Tweeted about it.

00:10:05.641 --> 00:10:07.390
Found there were a
whole lot of fight fans

00:10:07.390 --> 00:10:09.040
that retweeted my tweet.

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:10.800
But what I knew is he
was there because he

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:13.750
was doing a fundraiser
to fight diabetes.

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:16.540
And for me, I wanted to tweet
that because my mom had that

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:17.450
as well.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:20.810
So really, that's the story.

00:10:20.810 --> 00:10:23.920
But that's not the
reason I'm telling you.

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:25.650
A couple of years
ago, I was having

00:10:25.650 --> 00:10:29.980
dinner with a friend in Novato,
and a gentleman was at the bar.

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:32.200
We had forgotten to have
the waitress take a picture.

00:10:32.200 --> 00:10:35.770
By the way, now that we all
have cameras on our phones,

00:10:35.770 --> 00:10:38.580
we all want to take pictures.

00:10:38.580 --> 00:10:40.164
So I saw this
gentleman at the bar.

00:10:40.164 --> 00:10:41.330
There were only two of them.

00:10:41.330 --> 00:10:43.300
It was a rainy night in Marin.

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:45.640
And I said to my
friend, oh, I think

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:47.840
we can ask this gentleman
to take our picture.

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:50.070
He had a big welcoming smile.

00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:51.700
I went over with
my camera and said,

00:10:51.700 --> 00:10:54.930
would you please take a
picture of my friend and me?

00:10:54.930 --> 00:10:56.190
And he started to laugh.

00:10:56.190 --> 00:10:57.770
Of course.

00:10:57.770 --> 00:10:59.220
He took the picture.

00:10:59.220 --> 00:11:00.520
We walked out.

00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:02.640
We are in the lobby,
and my friend said,

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:07.710
I think that was Chris
Robinson from Black Crow.

00:11:07.710 --> 00:11:09.077
You mean I just asked Chris--?

00:11:09.077 --> 00:11:10.160
No wonder he was laughing.

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:13.040
He thought I was saying, can
I take a picture with you?

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:15.280
But I said, I think
I insulted him.

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:20.230
I must go back and
apologize to Chris Robinson

00:11:20.230 --> 00:11:23.320
and ask for a picture.

00:11:23.320 --> 00:11:28.010
And my friend said
to me, don't do that.

00:11:28.010 --> 00:11:32.390
You don't need to
talk to him again.

00:11:32.390 --> 00:11:34.320
Here's my lesson.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:38.050
Don't ever listen to
someone who tells you

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:42.870
what to do that doesn't have
your interest, your values,

00:11:42.870 --> 00:11:48.120
your confidence, and your
desire to do something,

00:11:48.120 --> 00:11:50.980
because they won't
be less comfortable.

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:54.662
But you'll walk away feeling,
gosh, I should have done that.

00:11:54.662 --> 00:11:56.870
Have any of you done that,
where someone said to you,

00:11:56.870 --> 00:11:57.670
don't do something?

00:11:57.670 --> 00:11:59.128
You listen to them,
and you though,

00:11:59.128 --> 00:12:01.670
oh my goodness, that's the best.

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:04.100
I'm never doing that again.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:05.019
I learned my lesson.

00:12:05.019 --> 00:12:06.810
And I wasn't going to
let that happen again

00:12:06.810 --> 00:12:09.310
with Sugar Ray Leonard.

00:12:09.310 --> 00:12:11.370
But working a room is work.

00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:15.010
In the book, I talk
about the road blocks

00:12:15.010 --> 00:12:17.790
besides the shyness,
the remedies,

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:22.790
and we talk about the
strategies to make conversation.

00:12:22.790 --> 00:12:26.580
I'm the original
small talk fan I

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:29.790
know there are a lot of people
that say, I'm really important.

00:12:29.790 --> 00:12:31.960
I can't waste my
time on small talk.

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:33.950
Let's say you're at an event.

00:12:33.950 --> 00:12:34.970
You're at a conference.

00:12:34.970 --> 00:12:36.060
You're at a Google event.

00:12:36.060 --> 00:12:37.650
You're at a fundraiser.

00:12:37.650 --> 00:12:42.800
And you're going to start
with war, famine, disease--

00:12:42.800 --> 00:12:46.990
all really important topics,
not the best opening line.

00:12:46.990 --> 00:12:48.960
So really, talking
about the little things

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:51.510
is how we find out how we
have something in common.

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:56.620
And you heard Cliff say that
I'm also a Fighting Illini.

00:12:56.620 --> 00:12:58.820
Here's how it happened.

00:12:58.820 --> 00:13:00.820
That picture, I was at an event.

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:03.640
And Jeff Huber, who is
a University of Illinois

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:07.620
grad with Google Labs,
he was our speaker.

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:13.810
And he brought Google Glass for
us to demonstrate and try on.

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:15.680
You'll notice I'm
wearing the orange pair--

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:19.100
because after all, orange
is our Illinois color.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:22.240
So I decided to send
Cliff that picture.

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:25.234
And I explained to him--
probably in more detail

00:13:25.234 --> 00:13:26.650
than he wanted to
know, but it was

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:30.700
significant-- saying why I was
wearing Google Glass, about

00:13:30.700 --> 00:13:32.980
Jeff, I went to Illinois.

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:35.650
I got back an email
from Cliff saying,

00:13:35.650 --> 00:13:37.510
you aren't going
to believe this.

00:13:37.510 --> 00:13:41.640
I went to Illinois, and
I grew up in Champagne.

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:45.180
You never know that little
bit of added detail,

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:49.600
that some people call small
talk, connects us to people.

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:53.990
How many of you have a
favorite sports team?

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:57.770
OK, what is your
favorite sports team?

00:13:57.770 --> 00:14:00.980
Your college football
team, which one is that?

00:14:00.980 --> 00:14:01.950
USC Trojans.

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:06.630
OK, I won't say that I was
there and Stanford fan here.

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:08.010
OK, I won't say that.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:09.410
Anyone else?

00:14:09.410 --> 00:14:10.500
Favorite teams?

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:12.860
Yes?

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:15.020
The Calgary Flames,
the hockey team?

00:14:15.020 --> 00:14:16.330
Yes, yes.

00:14:19.950 --> 00:14:22.350
Now really, did you
know him before?

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:24.240
Would you two please
turn around and look

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:29.410
at each-- we've got two
Calgary Flames teams.

00:14:29.410 --> 00:14:32.350
Actually, I know the team
well because my cousin

00:14:32.350 --> 00:14:37.870
lived in Calgary and was one
of the TV cameramen there.

00:14:37.870 --> 00:14:39.670
This is a little detail.

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:42.210
This is the perfect
example of how

00:14:42.210 --> 00:14:44.824
you find something in common.

00:14:44.824 --> 00:14:46.490
And I'm going to give
you the roadblock.

00:14:46.490 --> 00:14:49.280
The first roadblock, I call
the mother's dire warnings.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:52.320
The first one is, don't
talk to strangers.

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:54.170
How many of you heard
that growing up?

00:14:54.170 --> 00:14:55.409
Don't talk to strangers.

00:14:55.409 --> 00:14:57.200
The rest of you who
didn't raise your hand,

00:14:57.200 --> 00:14:58.408
your parents didn't love you.

00:15:01.660 --> 00:15:03.720
Don't talk to strangers,
that's sensible.

00:15:03.720 --> 00:15:05.070
That make sense.

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:10.220
When you're here at this amazing
campus, nobody is a stranger.

00:15:10.220 --> 00:15:13.620
We should be able to smile and
just say hello to everyone.

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:15.290
When I was writing
my third book,

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:17.140
I was at Time Warner building.

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:19.010
And one of the
things that happened

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:23.495
was that my editor
said, you know,

00:15:23.495 --> 00:15:28.090
we really don't go into
elevators with certain people.

00:15:28.090 --> 00:15:30.680
She said everybody
knows the receptionist.

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:31.320
I said, really?

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:32.240
She says, oh yeah.

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:34.210
When you see someone you
don't want to talk to

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:36.540
or you're kind of
afraid of the big boss,

00:15:36.540 --> 00:15:38.150
you talk to the receptionist.

00:15:38.150 --> 00:15:40.180
The receptionist
knew more people

00:15:40.180 --> 00:15:43.090
who worked for Time
Warner because people

00:15:43.090 --> 00:15:47.920
were afraid of having a
conversation in an elevator

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:52.060
with someone that they didn't
know-- who, by the way,

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:55.070
might be someone who could
tell them about another job

00:15:55.070 --> 00:15:56.950
that they might
be interested in.

00:15:56.950 --> 00:15:58.650
So instead of don't
talk to strangers,

00:15:58.650 --> 00:16:01.780
here's the remedy--
redefine a stranger.

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:02.810
This is old school.

00:16:02.810 --> 00:16:03.960
You're getting a handout.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.270
On the handout, it has
my contact information,

00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:10.330
but it also has five
tips and a bonus

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:12.710
that you could share with
other people if you like,

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:15.160
and the link to the
infographic, which

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:17.070
is the step by
step of how to work

00:16:17.070 --> 00:16:19.380
a room that's on my website.

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:22.100
But instead of don't talk to
strangers, redefine a stranger.

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:23.724
Everywhere you go,
you should think of,

00:16:23.724 --> 00:16:25.320
what do I have in
common with people?

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:26.990
Could be the Calgary Flames.

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:30.880
Anyone here like Chicago
style deep dish pizza?

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:32.760
Would you please
raise your hands?

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:35.210
We're going out afterwards
for deep dish pizza,

00:16:35.210 --> 00:16:37.563
or we'll get the
cafeteria to make--

00:16:37.563 --> 00:16:41.740
you know, some big arguments
over thin crust and deep dish

00:16:41.740 --> 00:16:42.460
pizza.

00:16:42.460 --> 00:16:45.690
And some people are going, well,
that's insignificant, silly

00:16:45.690 --> 00:16:47.650
conversation.

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:49.460
I'm from Chicago.

00:16:49.460 --> 00:16:52.710
When you talk thick,
deep dish pizza,

00:16:52.710 --> 00:16:54.730
that's not insignificant.

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:58.150
That's really important.

00:16:58.150 --> 00:17:01.380
Some people are laughing
because they know it's true.

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:05.810
The second thing that stops
us is often we will hear,

00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:07.430
gee, we should
only talk to people

00:17:07.430 --> 00:17:09.640
that we've been
properly introduced to.

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:12.940
Wouldn't you love to have
Cliff go with you everywhere?

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:14.440
And every time you
walk in a room,

00:17:14.440 --> 00:17:17.579
he says those grate
things about you?

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:20.220
A few trumpets, we could
have gotten here at Google,

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:22.349
would've been nice
to herald the entry.

00:17:22.349 --> 00:17:24.849
But really, we're on our own.

00:17:24.849 --> 00:17:27.190
So I want to give
you the remedy.

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:28.925
The remedy is,
everywhere you go,

00:17:28.925 --> 00:17:31.300
before you go there-- and let
me ask you, how many of you

00:17:31.300 --> 00:17:35.820
belong to other professional
groups off campus?

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:38.800
What do you belong to?

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:41.410
OK, so you belong to ACM, a
professional organization.

00:17:41.410 --> 00:17:42.950
I saw a hand over here.

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:49.550
Where do you-- oh, I
actually spoke for Cal CPA.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:55.150
So Cal CPA, Right it's northern
California society of CPAs.

00:17:55.150 --> 00:17:57.340
anyone else?

00:17:57.340 --> 00:17:58.920
Generally, we do other things.

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:01.870
Anyone's been to a party lately?

00:18:01.870 --> 00:18:03.260
Nobody invites Googlers.

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.780
Anyone been to a party?

00:18:07.780 --> 00:18:08.280
Yes?

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:11.360
Where was your party?

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:14.630
Moved into a new neighborhood
and the neighbors

00:18:14.630 --> 00:18:16.430
invited for barbecue.

00:18:16.430 --> 00:18:21.300
It's so good to know that really
this idea of the welcome wagon

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:25.390
and making people feel welcome
and comfortable still exists.

00:18:25.390 --> 00:18:27.330
Because look, when we
move into a neighborhood

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:30.850
and that feels good, when
we start a new project that

00:18:30.850 --> 00:18:33.540
feels good, feeling welcomed.

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:36.400
And that's what "How to
Work a Room" is about.

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:39.170
It's about making
people feel welcomed,

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:44.590
making people feel important,
and extending ourselves.

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:45.450
That's important.

00:18:45.450 --> 00:18:47.410
In fact, watch this.

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:48.760
Oh hi, I'm Susan RoAne.

00:18:48.760 --> 00:18:50.520
It's so nice to meet you.

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:52.304
SHANNON: Hi, I'm Shannon Lee.

00:18:52.304 --> 00:18:53.720
SUSAN ROANE: And
Shannon Lee-- did

00:18:53.720 --> 00:18:55.530
you hear that
enthusiasm in her voice?

00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:58.221
You should have seen this
big smile on her face.

00:18:58.221 --> 00:18:59.470
That's why I went over to her.

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:01.761
She's going, I'm never sitting
at the edge with someone

00:19:01.761 --> 00:19:04.190
with a microphone that can move.

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:06.630
When we go over to
someone and they

00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:10.700
have a smile on their face,
that makes it easier to do.

00:19:10.700 --> 00:19:17.130
But you'll notice what I did is
I leaned into the conversation.

00:19:17.130 --> 00:19:20.020
Doctor David Schwartz in
"The Magic of Thinking Big"

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:22.860
found that leaders
and the people

00:19:22.860 --> 00:19:26.160
we consider the big kahunas,
when they meet people, they

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:28.380
lean into the greeting.

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:30.870
And he said what he
found about these people

00:19:30.870 --> 00:19:34.340
that we call our leaders
is that by doing that,

00:19:34.340 --> 00:19:36.210
they welcome people.

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:39.630
They do something called
they extend themselves

00:19:39.630 --> 00:19:41.680
to other people.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:43.350
And what "How to Work
a Room" is about,

00:19:43.350 --> 00:19:45.600
is extending yourself to people.

00:19:45.600 --> 00:19:47.470
And I will give
you a difference.

00:19:47.470 --> 00:19:50.384
Instead of thinking, what can I
do to make myself comfortable?

00:19:50.384 --> 00:19:52.050
Some of you don't
have pens, some of you

00:19:52.050 --> 00:19:53.650
have your computers
and smartphones,

00:19:53.650 --> 00:19:55.770
and others are going
to memorize this

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:58.950
because the quiz is next week.

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:01.229
Instead of thinking about
making yourself comfortable,

00:20:01.229 --> 00:20:02.770
I'm going to give
you a different way

00:20:02.770 --> 00:20:04.340
of looking at this.

00:20:04.340 --> 00:20:08.510
What can you do to make other
people comfortable with you?

00:20:08.510 --> 00:20:11.130
When you try to make other
people comfortable with you,

00:20:11.130 --> 00:20:13.860
you are actually
more comfortable

00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:16.620
because they open up.

00:20:16.620 --> 00:20:18.510
And when they open
up, then you open up

00:20:18.510 --> 00:20:20.270
because they're
responding to you.

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:24.110
And what you have
is a conversation.

00:20:24.110 --> 00:20:28.010
So lean in to your greetings.

00:20:28.010 --> 00:20:31.760
Don't talk to strangers,
redefine a stranger.

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:36.100
Make sure that you know what
you have in common with people

00:20:36.100 --> 00:20:36.950
before you go there.

00:20:36.950 --> 00:20:37.980
It's so easy.

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:39.780
We get to Google events.

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:41.100
We get to learn about them.

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:43.100
We get to know who's
going to be there.

00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:44.580
We can find out about people.

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:45.710
We can go to LinkedIn.

00:20:45.710 --> 00:20:47.360
We can go to their websites.

00:20:47.360 --> 00:20:51.760
There's almost no reason
to go anywhere not knowing

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:54.760
who's going to be
there, or not knowing

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:56.770
the generic person of
who's going to be there

00:20:56.770 --> 00:20:59.295
and what you have
in common with them.

00:20:59.295 --> 00:21:00.670
But then there's
that other thing

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:03.800
that stops us, which we
would like that introduction.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:07.940
And I'm going to give you
three RoAne tips for what

00:21:07.940 --> 00:21:10.270
a self introduction is like.

00:21:10.270 --> 00:21:12.930
They're a little different
than what you've heard.

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:14.760
In fact, I just sent
a tweet yesterday

00:21:14.760 --> 00:21:17.030
that I send out periodically.

00:21:17.030 --> 00:21:19.830
Your self introduction
is not an upchucking

00:21:19.830 --> 00:21:21.950
of an elevator speech.

00:21:21.950 --> 00:21:25.240
A self introduction
is a pleasantry.

00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.660
It's not 15 or 30 seconds.

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:28.640
You're at an event.

00:21:28.640 --> 00:21:32.540
You have a beverage in one
hand and a significant dessert

00:21:32.540 --> 00:21:36.260
in the other, which would
mean lots of chocolate.

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:42.610
So what you do is,
instead of thinking, OK,

00:21:42.610 --> 00:21:44.320
what am I going to say?

00:21:44.320 --> 00:21:50.040
What you do is you do a seven
to nine second introduction.

00:21:50.040 --> 00:21:51.350
It's a pleasantry.

00:21:51.350 --> 00:21:56.310
Nobody wants to hear 15 to
20 to 30 seconds about you

00:21:56.310 --> 00:21:57.640
or what you do.

00:21:57.640 --> 00:21:58.897
It's a pleasantry.

00:21:58.897 --> 00:22:00.730
And you heard, it looks
and sounds -- oh hi,

00:22:00.730 --> 00:22:03.810
I'm Susan RoAne, it's
so nice to meet you.

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:07.870
And it should look and
sound like it's nice.

00:22:07.870 --> 00:22:09.550
This is the one
thing that I've kept

00:22:09.550 --> 00:22:13.330
in the book all
iterations for 25 years

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:17.020
because it's so important that
people know that we really

00:22:17.020 --> 00:22:19.800
need to feel
comfortable and make

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:23.080
other people
comfortable with us.

00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:24.510
Seven to nine seconds.

00:22:24.510 --> 00:22:27.490
But how I learned, the
reason why I wrote that is I

00:22:27.490 --> 00:22:31.040
was reading this book to edit
it and to change and update it

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:32.540
for this version.

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:34.880
And I went, that's why
I've been telling people

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:37.060
seven to nine seconds.

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:40.500
David Gibbons did
research on eye contact.

00:22:40.500 --> 00:22:43.400
And he found that
after nine seconds,

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:45.070
it's considered a glare.

00:22:48.840 --> 00:22:50.100
Thank goodness I read my book.

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:52.630
Now I can tell you
where that came from.

00:22:52.630 --> 00:22:55.560
Seven to nine seconds,
it's a pleasantry.

00:22:55.560 --> 00:22:58.210
The second aspect of
your self introduction

00:22:58.210 --> 00:23:03.220
anywhere is that it's
linked to the event.

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:06.270
So any time you're
with other Googlers,

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:08.897
you have something that
you're going to link to.

00:23:08.897 --> 00:23:09.730
You're at a wedding.

00:23:09.730 --> 00:23:11.790
So I had to say
at the wedding, I

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:15.210
don't know if I'm on the bride's
side or the groom's side.

00:23:15.210 --> 00:23:18.980
Because really, I could
have said, I'm Susan RoAne.

00:23:18.980 --> 00:23:23.390
I'm a fabulous keynote speaker
and a splendidly best selling

00:23:23.390 --> 00:23:25.530
author-- all of which were true.

00:23:25.530 --> 00:23:28.657
However, at a
wedding, nobody cares.

00:23:28.657 --> 00:23:30.365
They want to know, do
you know the bride?

00:23:30.365 --> 00:23:32.200
Do you know the groom?

00:23:32.200 --> 00:23:34.390
How did you come to be here?

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:37.080
Because you have to
give people context.

00:23:37.080 --> 00:23:38.960
And that's what I try
to do in the book--

00:23:38.960 --> 00:23:43.180
give everyone context for
whatever event they were at.

00:23:43.180 --> 00:23:45.120
So I had to tell them
why I didn't know.

00:23:45.120 --> 00:23:47.730
And the reason is,
I knew the bride.

00:23:47.730 --> 00:23:49.200
I met the groom.

00:23:49.200 --> 00:23:51.890
But in one of those
small talk conversations,

00:23:51.890 --> 00:23:54.940
he happened to mention
his uncle's name--

00:23:54.940 --> 00:23:59.950
which was different from
his-- and my ears perked up.

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:03.760
And I said, any
relation to Doctor Al?

00:24:03.760 --> 00:24:05.390
He goes, oh yeah.

00:24:05.390 --> 00:24:07.990
That's my grandfather.

00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:13.630
And I said to him,
my dad and your dad

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:16.230
and your grandfather
were dearest friends.

00:24:16.230 --> 00:24:19.440
And my mom and dad would
fly out from Chicago

00:24:19.440 --> 00:24:23.690
to visit your grandfather
and grandmother.

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:25.700
I didn't know what
side to sit on.

00:24:25.700 --> 00:24:29.072
But I embraced both of them.

00:24:29.072 --> 00:24:30.530
And why I tell you
this story, it's

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:33.520
always important to give people
a context for why you're there.

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:34.270
They don't know.

00:24:34.270 --> 00:24:35.810
What should they
talk to you about?

00:24:35.810 --> 00:24:38.810
But if you help them, it's
like the Jerry Maguire line--

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:44.600
"Help me help you." and
give people context.

00:24:44.600 --> 00:24:50.980
Another thing that
stops us, and that is we

00:24:50.980 --> 00:24:56.310
were told that good things
come to those who wait.

00:24:56.310 --> 00:24:57.680
How many of you heard that?

