00:37:34.080 --> 00:37:37.279
Be that good host
that she talked about.

00:37:37.279 --> 00:37:38.070
Here's what you do.

00:37:38.070 --> 00:37:40.278
The next time you see the
person, just say, you know?

00:37:40.278 --> 00:37:43.350
I just heard Susan RoAne talk
at one of our wonderful Google

00:37:43.350 --> 00:37:43.961
benefits.

00:37:43.961 --> 00:37:45.210
She said I should talk to you.

00:37:45.210 --> 00:37:46.150
I've seen you.

00:37:46.150 --> 00:37:47.160
You look interesting.

00:37:47.160 --> 00:37:47.800
Say something.

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:50.560
Blame me.

00:37:50.560 --> 00:37:52.930
Susan RoAne made me do it.

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:53.790
But don't wait.

00:37:53.790 --> 00:37:55.110
You have a great smile.

00:37:55.110 --> 00:37:58.140
You're so approachable
and easy to respond to.

00:37:58.140 --> 00:37:59.300
Say something.

00:37:59.300 --> 00:38:00.820
Because look, you're
asking me this.

00:38:00.820 --> 00:38:03.600
That means that you regret
that you haven't said anything.

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:05.280
No regrets.

00:38:05.280 --> 00:38:07.010
Here's the worst thing
that could happen.

00:38:07.010 --> 00:38:10.100
The person's going--
because they're shy.

00:38:10.100 --> 00:38:12.020
But give them a second chance.

00:38:12.020 --> 00:38:13.640
Because you know,
we think people

00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:15.780
back off because
they're not interested.

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:18.220
It could be their mind is
on a project they're doing.

00:38:18.220 --> 00:38:22.380
Or maybe they have to move
and they're thinking about,

00:38:22.380 --> 00:38:24.730
do I have to go to Craigslist
and look for an apartment?

00:38:24.730 --> 00:38:26.310
So you promise me.

00:38:26.310 --> 00:38:28.019
My email us on the
handout that you

00:38:28.019 --> 00:38:30.310
have in the back of the book
which you're going to buy.

00:38:30.310 --> 00:38:32.765
Would you please
send me an email?

00:38:32.765 --> 00:38:37.210
Yeah, you know, I mean, it's
supporting a local bookstore.

00:38:37.210 --> 00:38:39.300
Would you please
email me and let

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:40.760
me know what the response was?

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:41.450
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:43.580
SUSAN ROANE: Any
other questions?

00:38:43.580 --> 00:38:44.530
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:38:44.530 --> 00:38:48.520
My question is, how do you
break into a conversation that's

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:51.425
already ongoing when
you walk into a room?

00:38:51.425 --> 00:38:53.300
SUSAN ROANE: How many
of you had that happen?

00:38:53.300 --> 00:38:55.133
You walk in a room and
everyone's in groups,

00:38:55.133 --> 00:38:58.060
and you want to walk out?

00:38:58.060 --> 00:38:59.410
All of us.

00:38:59.410 --> 00:39:00.320
Here's what you do.

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:02.200
In this section in
"How to Work a Room,"

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:03.190
I've kept this section.

00:39:03.190 --> 00:39:05.800
I call it breaking and entering.

00:39:05.800 --> 00:39:07.010
So here's what you do.

00:39:07.010 --> 00:39:09.430
You see, you walk into the room.

00:39:09.430 --> 00:39:12.540
Hint from shy people--
the research, and this

00:39:12.540 --> 00:39:17.000
is social science research--
shy people almost never make

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:18.850
a grand entrance.

00:39:18.850 --> 00:39:22.540
They usually come to
an event no later than

00:39:22.540 --> 00:39:25.950
15 minutes after it's
called, because they don't

00:39:25.950 --> 00:39:27.720
want to see everyone in a group.

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:30.190
So that's what
your new mantra is.

00:39:30.190 --> 00:39:33.920
Get there on time, or only
15 minutes after it's called.

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:35.290
Look around the room.

00:39:35.290 --> 00:39:39.710
Pick the group that's
having the best time.

00:39:39.710 --> 00:39:40.210
Why?

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:42.710
Because they'll be
easier to walk into.

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:47.020
Pick the upbeat group of at
least three but four people.

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.910
Because you can be
sure four people

00:39:48.910 --> 00:39:51.790
aren't having an
intimate conversation.

00:39:51.790 --> 00:39:53.820
And if they are,
that's the group

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:57.020
I'd like to be talking to,
because that would be fun.

00:39:57.020 --> 00:40:02.350
But what you do is you
stand in the periphery.

00:40:02.350 --> 00:40:06.880
And when someone looks your
way, you say something just

00:40:06.880 --> 00:40:08.520
about the conversation
they're having.

00:40:08.520 --> 00:40:11.170
It's not the time to
change to your subject.

00:40:11.170 --> 00:40:15.246
And then you can step in and
continue the conversation.

00:40:15.246 --> 00:40:16.870
But I had someone
who was from Toronto.

00:40:16.870 --> 00:40:18.703
And my mother was from
Toronto, and she just

00:40:18.703 --> 00:40:21.710
thought Canadians are so much
more polite than we were.

00:40:21.710 --> 00:40:24.910
And then this woman said this
in my seminar in New York,

00:40:24.910 --> 00:40:26.490
and I thought it was genius.

00:40:26.490 --> 00:40:29.930
She said to me-- she always
had a big smile on her face.

00:40:29.930 --> 00:40:33.680
She'd go to a room, pick that
group that was having the most

00:40:33.680 --> 00:40:36.050
fun, and she'd stand
on the periphery.

00:40:36.050 --> 00:40:41.120
And when someone would look
her way, what she did is,

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:47.450
she said-- big smile-- do
you mind if I join you?

00:40:47.450 --> 00:40:48.940
What a brilliant idea.

00:40:48.940 --> 00:40:54.460
She said nobody ever said, "No,
as a matter of fact, we do."

00:40:54.460 --> 00:40:56.710
No one ever said that.

00:40:56.710 --> 00:40:59.000
And then she was part
of the conversation.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:03.700
But I'm going to make
this my Google get,

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:05.940
so here's what you do.

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:09.730
When you're at any
event-- social, business--

00:41:09.730 --> 00:41:12.910
and you see someone with your
peripheral vision, which we all

00:41:12.910 --> 00:41:16.830
have, that you know wants
to get in the group,

00:41:16.830 --> 00:41:19.450
you be the mingling
maven, that great host.

00:41:19.450 --> 00:41:23.160
Take one step back.

00:41:23.160 --> 00:41:25.500
Because when you
take a step back,

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:29.560
you will have included the
person who's been excluded.

00:41:29.560 --> 00:41:32.270
There's no reason to talk
about diversity and inclusion

00:41:32.270 --> 00:41:34.880
if we don't step back
and include people.

00:41:34.880 --> 00:41:36.640
Would people remember
the person that

00:41:36.640 --> 00:41:39.010
makes them feel welcome
and comfortable?

00:41:39.010 --> 00:41:40.200
I think so.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:43.020
So that would be how to get in.

00:41:43.020 --> 00:41:44.010
Does that make sense?

00:41:44.010 --> 00:41:44.850
Does that help?

00:41:44.850 --> 00:41:46.620
And we have another question.

00:41:46.620 --> 00:41:49.150
AUDIENCE: And since
you mentioned Croatia,

00:41:49.150 --> 00:41:53.720
how do you approach somebody
who's from another culture?

00:41:53.720 --> 00:41:56.950
Should you assume that you
know about his culture,

00:41:56.950 --> 00:41:59.470
if you know a few bits about it?

00:41:59.470 --> 00:42:04.120
Or should you approach
him with a blank slate,

00:42:04.120 --> 00:42:10.100
like completely trying
to be completely open?

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:12.470
SUSAN ROANE: You shouldn't
do what I just did.

00:42:12.470 --> 00:42:13.620
But here's the one thing.

00:42:13.620 --> 00:42:16.030
If you know a little
something about the culture

00:42:16.030 --> 00:42:18.460
that you can make the
person more comfortable,

00:42:18.460 --> 00:42:21.120
I say go ahead and
observe whatever

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:24.230
those cultural norms are.

00:42:24.230 --> 00:42:26.230
But most people are forgiving.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:29.390
I think if you show
interest and you're friendly

00:42:29.390 --> 00:42:32.350
and you're open,
people don't assume

00:42:32.350 --> 00:42:35.320
that you know everything
about their culture.

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:39.880
And how about this, here's a
great way to find out, is say,

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:41.170
I just wanted to meet you.

00:42:41.170 --> 00:42:46.650
I didn't want to do anything
that was inappropriate.

00:42:46.650 --> 00:42:48.440
I hope I haven't.

00:42:48.440 --> 00:42:50.500
And ask them.

00:42:50.500 --> 00:42:53.070
People will tell you, they're
happy to espouse that.

00:42:53.070 --> 00:42:55.390
But I think the fact
that you approach people,

00:42:55.390 --> 00:42:57.420
don't let that stop you.

00:42:57.420 --> 00:43:00.260
Right in this room, we have
people from different cultures.

00:43:00.260 --> 00:43:02.840
And you were all
talking up a storm.

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:05.250
Nothing stopped you from
talking to other people

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:07.070
in our little exercise, did it?

00:43:07.070 --> 00:43:08.950
So keep on doing that.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:11.640
I always figure,
if we ask people,

00:43:11.640 --> 00:43:14.640
that's the way we learn
about people's cultures is

00:43:14.640 --> 00:43:16.932
we find out by asking.

00:43:16.932 --> 00:43:19.340
Does that makes sense to you?

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:20.080
Anyone else?

00:43:20.080 --> 00:43:21.300
Oh yes, my new friend.

00:43:21.300 --> 00:43:22.600
OK.

00:43:22.600 --> 00:43:26.690
AUDIENCE: In one situation, I
was sitting in a shuttle bus

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:28.680
and trying to have a
conversation with somebody

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:29.880
that I don't know.

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:33.750
But he works in the same
company but had no interest

00:43:33.750 --> 00:43:35.800
in having a
conversation with me.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:36.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:36.780 --> 00:43:40.870
And in fact, one time
he offered carpooling

00:43:40.870 --> 00:43:42.590
to go back to the
shuttle bus station.

00:43:42.590 --> 00:43:45.960
So we were sitting together
for about half an hour.

00:43:45.960 --> 00:43:47.610
And I kept on asking
him questions.

00:43:47.610 --> 00:43:50.420
He never asked me a
single question back.

00:43:50.420 --> 00:43:55.470
So in a situation like this,
how could you overcome?

00:43:55.470 --> 00:43:57.820
SUSAN ROANE: OK.

00:43:57.820 --> 00:43:59.070
A couple of things.

00:43:59.070 --> 00:44:03.760
Number one, that person might
really be completely shy.

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:05.360
That's one thing.

00:44:05.360 --> 00:44:10.030
But I'm now going to put on
my judgmental hat and say,

00:44:10.030 --> 00:44:12.340
and maybe that person
had no confidence,

00:44:12.340 --> 00:44:15.730
but maybe that person was so
focused on what they're doing

00:44:15.730 --> 00:44:18.434
that they really didn't--
they shut out people.

00:44:18.434 --> 00:44:20.600
There are people that say
that they're introverts so

00:44:20.600 --> 00:44:23.020
that they really don't
want to talk to people.

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:26.350
I think when someone is
not interested at all,

00:44:26.350 --> 00:44:28.150
they say that on an airplane.

00:44:28.150 --> 00:44:31.060
There's some of us like to
talk and some of us don't.

00:44:31.060 --> 00:44:33.740
Believe it or not, I'm one of
the people that don't talk.

00:44:33.740 --> 00:44:34.970
And there's a reason.

00:44:34.970 --> 00:44:37.090
The speech therapist
says those of us

00:44:37.090 --> 00:44:41.330
who speak for a living shouldn't
gulp in all that recycled air.

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:42.810
It harms your vocal cords.

00:44:42.810 --> 00:44:45.780
With that person, I
would try someone else.

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:48.690
That's where-- by the way,
when you're talking to someone

00:44:48.690 --> 00:44:52.180
and they're not interested
and you give it two and three

00:44:52.180 --> 00:44:58.130
times, there are 100 other
people that are nice.

00:44:58.130 --> 00:45:00.500
I won't even say what I
would have said in Chicago,

00:45:00.500 --> 00:45:02.130
other than we had
a really big lake,

00:45:02.130 --> 00:45:03.800
and we bought
people cement shoes.

00:45:03.800 --> 00:45:05.799
Just as a thought.

00:45:05.799 --> 00:45:07.090
I think you've done everything.

00:45:07.090 --> 00:45:08.390
You have a great smile.

00:45:08.390 --> 00:45:11.630
But after that, go
to the next person.

00:45:11.630 --> 00:45:14.100
AUDIENCE: Question is
a little bit different.

00:45:14.100 --> 00:45:18.640
How do you manage knowing a lot
of people and staying in touch?

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:21.500
Because I tend to meet
people from everywhere,

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:22.300
all over the world.

00:45:22.300 --> 00:45:23.950
I live in so many
different places.

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:26.880
And I generally like
a lot of those people.

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:29.129
But it gets sometimes
so difficult,

00:45:29.129 --> 00:45:31.170
and I feel like I'm having
an Alzheimer's and I'm

00:45:31.170 --> 00:45:33.937
forgetting people's
names and faces.

00:45:33.937 --> 00:45:36.020
SUSAN ROANE: As long as
you don't forget your own,

00:45:36.020 --> 00:45:38.440
you're OK.

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:39.660
I think that that happens.

00:45:39.660 --> 00:45:41.380
This is why it's
beautiful that we

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:43.720
could have LinkedIn and
Facebook, et cetera,

00:45:43.720 --> 00:45:45.540
because we can stay
in touch with people--

00:45:45.540 --> 00:45:49.330
a little touch, a little
poke, a little tweet.

00:45:49.330 --> 00:45:51.140
But it really is about
staying in touch.

00:45:51.140 --> 00:45:53.990
And here's the other thing--
it's an investment of time.

00:45:53.990 --> 00:45:56.920
And it doesn't mean you stay in
touch with everyone every day,

00:45:56.920 --> 00:45:58.782
but a little note
that just lets people

00:45:58.782 --> 00:45:59.990
know you're thinking of them.

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:02.040
And that's when we
know a lot of people

00:46:02.040 --> 00:46:05.650
and we have this huge
network and we like people.

00:46:05.650 --> 00:46:08.355
I would say, I'd
invest that time--

00:46:08.355 --> 00:46:09.980
and you could be
multitasking and doing

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:11.730
something else at
the same time--

00:46:11.730 --> 00:46:15.980
to stay in touch with people
you really know and like.

00:46:15.980 --> 00:46:17.855
Because in the long
haul, what you develop

00:46:17.855 --> 00:46:21.060
is a network of really
great people in your life

00:46:21.060 --> 00:46:27.100
that you can count on
and who can count on you.

00:46:27.100 --> 00:46:29.300
I think this is where
social networking is

00:46:29.300 --> 00:46:31.719
a wonderful opportunity
of staying in touch.

00:46:31.719 --> 00:46:32.510
You know what I do?

00:46:32.510 --> 00:46:34.640
And I don't even remember
who I gave my phone to.

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:37.760
When I go back and look
at my pictures-- oh,

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:40.090
he put it in his pocket.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:43.400
Wait till he finds out that the
case is from Claire's and it's

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:44.600
bejeweled.

00:46:44.600 --> 00:46:46.100
It's going to be
very interesting.

00:46:46.100 --> 00:46:46.930
You know what I do?

00:46:46.930 --> 00:46:48.770
I go back to the photos.

00:46:48.770 --> 00:46:52.420
And I'll see a photo I took
with someone or of someone.

00:46:52.420 --> 00:46:56.230
And I'll just quickly text
it to them or email and say,

00:46:56.230 --> 00:46:57.420
I saw this photo.

00:46:57.420 --> 00:47:00.260
Was thinking of the
wonderful memory.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:02.962
And it's just a wonderful way
to stay in touch with people.

00:47:02.962 --> 00:47:04.920
But I'm going to give
you the hint from secrets

00:47:04.920 --> 00:47:10.150
of savvy networking-- one by
you-- you can work a room.

00:47:10.150 --> 00:47:11.380
You can engage.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:12.540
You can connect.

00:47:12.540 --> 00:47:15.340
But if you don't follow up
and stay in touch with people,

00:47:15.340 --> 00:47:19.800
you don't have that network
of friends that you need.

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:22.840
Because the followup
is essential.

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:24.830
The best traits of
savvy networkers,

00:47:24.830 --> 00:47:27.860
they follow up when they say
they're going to follow up

00:47:27.860 --> 00:47:29.940
and do what they say
they're going to do.

00:47:29.940 --> 00:47:31.720
You can invite
people on LinkedIn.

00:47:31.720 --> 00:47:34.790
You can invite them on
whatever Google company board

00:47:34.790 --> 00:47:36.370
that you have.

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:37.950
But stay in touch with people.

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:39.210
Don't wait for them.

00:47:39.210 --> 00:47:43.070
Remember what I said, initiate.

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:45.549
Be the person that
extends yourself.

00:47:45.549 --> 00:47:46.590
Because what do you want?

00:47:46.590 --> 00:47:48.640
Don't you all want
a network of people

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:52.190
that help you grow as you
move forward in your careers?

00:47:52.190 --> 00:47:53.890
That's how you get them.

00:47:53.890 --> 00:47:56.249
And then sometimes they'll
even cook you a meal.

00:47:56.249 --> 00:47:58.540
AUDIENCE: I think a lot of
times what's holding me back

00:47:58.540 --> 00:48:01.180
from the initiating a
conversation is I'm not sure

00:48:01.180 --> 00:48:03.560
if I can end it smoothly.

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:05.290
As a matter of fact,
I think it's easier

00:48:05.290 --> 00:48:08.740
to start a conversation
than to end it.

00:48:08.740 --> 00:48:09.974
Do you have tricks?

00:48:09.974 --> 00:48:11.390
SUSAN ROANE: You
are on the money.

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:15.380
I'm going to give you one
of my books as a present.

00:48:15.380 --> 00:48:19.310
That is the number one question
I've been asked, not 25 years,

00:48:19.310 --> 00:48:21.340
30 years that I've been
talking about this.

00:48:21.340 --> 00:48:23.275
And what he said
is, how do you end?

00:48:23.275 --> 00:48:26.890
And a lot of people don't start
because they don't want to end,

00:48:26.890 --> 00:48:28.920
because we don't want to
hurt people's feelings

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:32.500
and we want a gracious
ending, right?

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:36.040
Three ways to end conversations.

00:48:36.040 --> 00:48:38.510
It's also on my
website on my blog.

00:48:38.510 --> 00:48:40.750
But three ways to end
conversations-- and it's

00:48:40.750 --> 00:48:42.170
in the book.

00:48:42.170 --> 00:48:44.850
First way, when you've
had a great conversation

00:48:44.850 --> 00:48:47.860
with someone, oh, it's
so nice to talk to you

00:48:47.860 --> 00:48:51.640
about the 49ers and
their draft picks.

00:48:51.640 --> 00:48:55.060
I just made that up, but that
is what I've been talking about.

00:48:55.060 --> 00:48:56.800
Now notice.

00:48:56.800 --> 00:49:00.039
Shook hands, I didn't
necessarily lean in,

00:49:00.039 --> 00:49:01.830
but it was so nice to
talk to you about it.

00:49:01.830 --> 00:49:04.670
And then I summarized
a little phrase

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:07.050
so he knows I was
listening and that I

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:08.950
was part of that conversation.

00:49:08.950 --> 00:49:12.070
So nice to talk to you about.

00:49:12.070 --> 00:49:14.210
And then what you
do is, if you want

00:49:14.210 --> 00:49:16.290
their card-- do we
still give out cards?

00:49:16.290 --> 00:49:18.250
I saw them at Google.

00:49:18.250 --> 00:49:21.290
I had one guy on a plane said to
me, oh, I take people's cards,

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:23.110
take a picture,
and throw them out.

00:49:23.110 --> 00:49:25.560
Well, that makes me feel good.

00:49:25.560 --> 00:49:27.330
You could have not told me that.

00:49:27.330 --> 00:49:29.790
But exchange cards.

00:49:29.790 --> 00:49:31.290
And what if you
want someone's card?

00:49:31.290 --> 00:49:33.430
Oh, do you have a card?

00:49:33.430 --> 00:49:35.810
Now, I once asked that to a
gentleman who looked at me--

00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:38.585
I tell you-- totally
deadpan and said, yes.

00:49:44.020 --> 00:49:45.380
OK, could I have one?

00:49:45.380 --> 00:49:47.270
About 20 years later,
I said, tell me.

00:49:47.270 --> 00:49:49.970
Why did you just say yes
and not give me a card?

00:49:49.970 --> 00:49:55.630
Here was his answer--
you hadn't asked for one.

00:49:55.630 --> 00:49:57.130
Don't play card games.

00:49:57.130 --> 00:49:57.640
It's silly.

00:49:57.640 --> 00:49:59.910
That's a waste of time.

00:49:59.910 --> 00:50:01.360
So ask for someone's card.

00:50:01.360 --> 00:50:03.740
And then what if they
don't ask for yours?

00:50:03.740 --> 00:50:07.740
What you could say-- and this is
completely contrarian to those

00:50:07.740 --> 00:50:10.820
who want to get to the
point-- don't save time.

00:50:10.820 --> 00:50:13.260
Say, may I offer
you one of mine?

00:50:13.260 --> 00:50:15.230
May I please offer
you one of mine?

00:50:15.230 --> 00:50:17.090
Well, why don't I
just give them a card?

00:50:17.090 --> 00:50:20.550
Because there's something about
the manners and the etiquette

00:50:20.550 --> 00:50:23.300
and showing that
you have manners

00:50:23.300 --> 00:50:26.110
that's really memorable.

00:50:26.110 --> 00:50:28.430
OK, then here's what I would do.

00:50:28.430 --> 00:50:33.460
I would then walk a quarter of
the room away to someone else.

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:34.660
(WHISPERING) Here's my book.

00:50:34.660 --> 00:50:39.214
No, to someone else
who is standing alone,

00:50:39.214 --> 00:50:41.380
because I know he doesn't
want to be standing alone,

00:50:41.380 --> 00:50:43.220
or to another group of people.

00:50:43.220 --> 00:50:46.070
But walking a quarter
of the room away

00:50:46.070 --> 00:50:48.570
is really important, because
that way you don't make someone

00:50:48.570 --> 00:50:51.544
feel you've just turned
your back on them.

00:50:51.544 --> 00:50:53.210
That's where that
expression comes from.

00:50:53.210 --> 00:50:54.550
Does that make sense?

00:50:54.550 --> 00:50:58.220
Another way that you
exit-- and by the way,

00:50:58.220 --> 00:50:59.340
that gives you the card.

00:50:59.340 --> 00:51:02.330
Then you can follow up later
and invite them to LinkedIn

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:05.140
and connect and send an email.

00:51:05.140 --> 00:51:07.450
I know that sounds antiquated,
but once in awhile,

00:51:07.450 --> 00:51:08.550
I even do that.

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:10.200
And how about this?

00:51:10.200 --> 00:51:11.700
Sometimes if you
had a conversation

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:13.830
that you really want to
continue and you've both

00:51:13.830 --> 00:51:16.830
talked about
continuing it, here's

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:19.520
a really interesting thought.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:25.060
You can take out your
phones, get that phone app,

00:51:25.060 --> 00:51:28.400
and call them.

00:51:28.400 --> 00:51:31.920
That will really show
how different you are.

00:51:31.920 --> 00:51:32.870
You pick up the phone.

00:51:32.870 --> 00:51:35.644
And by the way, those of you
who have the book, somewhere

00:51:35.644 --> 00:51:37.060
in the book-- and
I can't remember

00:51:37.060 --> 00:51:41.090
where-- there is a
QR code and a URL.

00:51:41.090 --> 00:51:44.140
But if you run your phone
over it or you plug in the URL

00:51:44.140 --> 00:51:51.020
to your browser, you get a
special, online-only extra

00:51:51.020 --> 00:51:53.475
chapter that has to
do with the phone.

00:51:53.475 --> 00:51:55.100
And I wish I could
tell you which page,

00:51:55.100 --> 00:51:57.030
but I don't remember.

00:51:57.030 --> 00:51:59.744
Talk about not
remembering things.

00:51:59.744 --> 00:52:00.910
Oh, there's one on the back.

00:52:00.910 --> 00:52:01.920
That leads to a video.

00:52:01.920 --> 00:52:05.477
But the one inside leads to
a special online chapter.

00:52:05.477 --> 00:52:07.560
Thank you, he pointed out
what I should have said.

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:11.320
I tried to make this book
in 25 years interactive.

00:52:11.320 --> 00:52:13.170
So on the back,
there's a QR code.

00:52:13.170 --> 00:52:15.540
And when you run your
phone over it, what it does

00:52:15.540 --> 00:52:17.500
is up pops a video
of me saying what's

00:52:17.500 --> 00:52:18.950
different and new in the book.

00:52:18.950 --> 00:52:21.670
So did that help
you, how to exit?

00:52:21.670 --> 00:52:23.720
Let's just say-- let me
give you another exit.

00:52:23.720 --> 00:52:25.600
Let's say you had a
conversation with someone

00:52:25.600 --> 00:52:27.390
and it wasn't going anywhere.

00:52:27.390 --> 00:52:29.120
Here's what you do.

00:52:29.120 --> 00:52:31.120
Don't say, I've had a
great time talking to you,

00:52:31.120 --> 00:52:32.640
because it hasn't
been a great time.

00:52:32.640 --> 00:52:35.040
It's been like pulling
teeth, a little root canal.

00:52:35.040 --> 00:52:38.950
So what you say to them is-- and
don't any of you say this to me

00:52:38.950 --> 00:52:44.520
later-- I hope you enjoy
the rest of the event.

00:52:44.520 --> 00:52:45.900
Big smile.

00:52:45.900 --> 00:52:47.595
And you still walk a
quarter of the room

00:52:47.595 --> 00:52:50.230
away, because that person might
be thinking about something

00:52:50.230 --> 00:52:54.430
else that happened at home,
and they're not responsive

00:52:54.430 --> 00:52:56.300
because they're distracted.

00:52:56.300 --> 00:52:59.560
But the next time you see
them, it might be wonderful.

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:02.410
And then the third
one isn't really

00:53:02.410 --> 00:53:03.570
moving away from someone.

00:53:03.570 --> 00:53:06.602
The third one is, oh, I see Joe.

00:53:06.602 --> 00:53:07.310
Have you met him?

00:53:07.310 --> 00:53:08.480
Why don't you come on over?

00:53:08.480 --> 00:53:10.400
It's called the bring along.

00:53:10.400 --> 00:53:12.610
And then you're in a
group conversation.

00:53:12.610 --> 00:53:14.300
So you have three ways to exit.

00:53:14.300 --> 00:53:16.110
Well, one question
I'm often asked

00:53:16.110 --> 00:53:18.190
is, what do I do
if I forgot a name?

00:53:18.190 --> 00:53:21.930
Have any of you
encountered that?

00:53:21.930 --> 00:53:24.030
OK, here's what you do.

00:53:24.030 --> 00:53:27.040
I know that there are name
and memory specialists that

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:30.070
will tell you, much
like Doctor Seuss,

00:53:30.070 --> 00:53:34.230
to put a cat in a vat
in a hat on their head.

00:53:34.230 --> 00:53:36.660
But what I would say is, when
you forgot someone's name

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:40.620
and you know their face is
familiar, save some time

00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:44.730
and go over and say, it's
just been one of those days.

00:53:44.730 --> 00:53:46.120
I know your face.

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:47.270
I know we've met.

00:53:47.270 --> 00:53:52.280
Could you help me out and
remind me of your name?

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:53.080
It's direct.

00:53:53.080 --> 00:53:54.760
Now here's what happens.

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:57.940
Every person has
forgotten someone's name.

00:53:57.940 --> 00:54:01.780
If it's your sister or your
mother-in-law, not so cool.

00:54:01.780 --> 00:54:04.230
But people have
forgotten people's names.

00:54:04.230 --> 00:54:06.840
And then they'll tell you
stories how they forgot a name.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:09.640
But if you say that
up front, that works.

00:54:09.640 --> 00:54:10.892
But here's another technique.

00:54:10.892 --> 00:54:12.350
And I learned this
from a gentleman

00:54:12.350 --> 00:54:15.265
who was the vice president
of the Harlem Globetrotters.

00:54:15.265 --> 00:54:17.640
Well, I knew he was the vice
president in the main office

00:54:17.640 --> 00:54:19.150
because he was 5'5.

00:54:19.150 --> 00:54:20.670
But he told me this.

00:54:20.670 --> 00:54:23.740
He said-- and I kept this in
the book 25 years-- he said,

00:54:23.740 --> 00:54:27.080
Susan, what you tell people
is when they go somewhere

00:54:27.080 --> 00:54:30.580
and they see someone that
they recognize but they really

00:54:30.580 --> 00:54:33.540
don't remember a name,
he said, always-- even

00:54:33.540 --> 00:54:36.330
if you've seen that
person five times--

00:54:36.330 --> 00:54:38.980
always put your hand
out and say your name.

00:54:38.980 --> 00:54:40.880
Hi, I'm Susan RoAne.

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:41.732
VINCE: Vince Lacey.

00:54:41.732 --> 00:54:42.440
SUSAN ROANE: Yes.

00:54:42.440 --> 00:54:44.523
He's just looking at me
smiling, going, oh my God.

00:54:44.523 --> 00:54:45.820
I'm not safe from her.

00:54:45.820 --> 00:54:48.890
OK, here's what Manny said.

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:51.900
When you go over
and say your name,

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:54.930
you can bet if you didn't
remember their name after six

00:54:54.930 --> 00:54:57.690
months, they have no
clue of your name either.

00:54:57.690 --> 00:55:00.640
But when you see your
name, 90% of the time,

00:55:00.640 --> 00:55:02.290
people will respond in kind.

00:55:02.290 --> 00:55:04.330
Then you both know
each other and reminded

00:55:04.330 --> 00:55:05.630
each other of your names.

00:55:05.630 --> 00:55:08.160
And then you're
having a conversation.

00:55:08.160 --> 00:55:12.740
Does that help you
around remembering names?

00:55:12.740 --> 00:55:14.810
And then just tell the truth.

00:55:14.810 --> 00:55:16.660
I'm going to have
any more questions,

00:55:16.660 --> 00:55:19.300
and then I'm going to close.

00:55:19.300 --> 00:55:19.800
Any more?

00:55:19.800 --> 00:55:21.130
Who has the microphone?

00:55:21.130 --> 00:55:21.940
Oh, you do.

00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:23.049
Any questions, Cliff?

00:55:23.049 --> 00:55:25.090
CLIFF: I think we're set
a questions for now, so.

00:55:25.090 --> 00:55:26.790
SUSAN ROANE: OK.

00:55:26.790 --> 00:55:29.170
Working a room is work.

00:55:29.170 --> 00:55:31.180
I've had people say-- and
I'm going to stay here

00:55:31.180 --> 00:55:32.280
so that I sign the book.

00:55:32.280 --> 00:55:36.152
I once was signing a book,
and I was writing a sentence.

00:55:36.152 --> 00:55:37.860
And the guy looked at
me and say, really?

00:55:37.860 --> 00:55:40.444
You write a whole
lot for an autograph.

00:55:40.444 --> 00:55:41.860
Because I don't
just sign my name.

00:55:41.860 --> 00:55:45.350
And I said, really,
the autograph was easy.

00:55:45.350 --> 00:55:49.200
Writing the book, really
hard, but well worth it.

00:55:49.200 --> 00:55:53.570
Because I know it's served
people over a number of years

00:55:53.570 --> 00:55:56.870
and continues to serve
people, because I want you all

00:55:56.870 --> 00:56:01.030
to be able to walk into any
room and have a good time

00:56:01.030 --> 00:56:02.354
and meet who you want to meet.

00:56:02.354 --> 00:56:04.770
And by the way, when you're
wearing anything from Google--

00:56:04.770 --> 00:56:08.490
I saw the Google girl power and
I've seen some Google shirts--

00:56:08.490 --> 00:56:11.270
it starts conversations.

00:56:11.270 --> 00:56:14.670
I have a shirt that
says, "Give me chocolate,

00:56:14.670 --> 00:56:17.300
and nobody will get hurt."

00:56:17.300 --> 00:56:19.470
It starts conversations.

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:23.200
I'm good to end with something
that actually happened.

00:56:23.200 --> 00:56:24.960
When "How to Work a
Room" first came out,

00:56:24.960 --> 00:56:27.400
I spoke for the
Commonwealth Club.

00:56:27.400 --> 00:56:33.510
It was absolutely an honor
for me, a former teacher.

00:56:33.510 --> 00:56:36.170
Two men were in the second row.

00:56:36.170 --> 00:56:37.540
But I went before the talk.

00:56:37.540 --> 00:56:39.750
I held the book, my
baby, under my arm

00:56:39.750 --> 00:56:42.420
and I-- what brought you here?

00:56:42.420 --> 00:56:45.045
It was so nice to see
you, thank you for coming.

00:56:45.045 --> 00:56:47.586
And then one of them looked at
me with the face, and he says,

00:56:47.586 --> 00:56:49.500
I just have a
question to ask you.

00:56:49.500 --> 00:56:51.390
This is before the talk.

00:56:51.390 --> 00:56:53.400
I knew it wasn't going
to be a good one.

00:56:53.400 --> 00:56:59.140
He said, how did you
take a 200 page book

00:56:59.140 --> 00:57:03.710
and think you're going
to give a 45 minute talk?

00:57:03.710 --> 00:57:06.540
Well, there's
something about humor--

00:57:06.540 --> 00:57:09.170
and I wrote about in the
book-- that I channeled

00:57:09.170 --> 00:57:12.750
my grandfather, who was known as
having a great sense of humor.

00:57:12.750 --> 00:57:15.490
And I was so lucky the
answer came to me then

00:57:15.490 --> 00:57:19.110
that might have happened an
hour later while I hit my head.

00:57:19.110 --> 00:57:20.350
And I looked at the guy.

00:57:20.350 --> 00:57:22.599
And I said, the only way you
can handle someone that's

00:57:22.599 --> 00:57:24.760
sounding so negative
is with humor.

00:57:24.760 --> 00:57:27.710
And I said to him, you
think that was tough?

00:57:27.710 --> 00:57:32.920
I took a 45 minute talk and
turned it into a 200 page book.

00:57:32.920 --> 00:57:35.920
And now you have the
300 page version.

00:57:35.920 --> 00:57:38.030
And it's the silver anniversary.

00:57:38.030 --> 00:57:41.430
And I am so delighted
to be here at Google.

00:57:41.430 --> 00:57:43.430
I can't thank Cliff enough.

00:57:43.430 --> 00:57:45.710
We now have a whole
new room of-- I've

00:57:45.710 --> 00:57:47.740
anointed you the
mingling mavens.

00:57:47.740 --> 00:57:48.880
You have my email.

00:57:48.880 --> 00:57:51.910
Any questions that come up
that I haven't answered,

00:57:51.910 --> 00:57:54.900
feel free to let me know.

00:57:54.900 --> 00:57:57.800
And I promise you an answer.

00:57:57.800 --> 00:58:02.440
So thank you very much, and
I hope you'll tell every one.

00:58:02.440 --> 00:58:07.360
And I'm available, and I'll
keep on Googling, you guys.

00:58:07.360 --> 00:58:08.610
Thank you so much.

00:58:08.610 --> 00:58:09.810
[APPLAUSE]

00:58:09.810 --> 00:58:13.460
Thank you, thank you.

